{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":21,"record_hash":"sha256:1eb90f101b7656f6ec67e4ee9ed0f4c127bf2048e2db799cd2db5441fe6693d0","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:16:18.823Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 242e45\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1683\nOutput:\n# Agent Trail\n\nAgent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\nIt is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\nbehind a change.\n\n## Working Name\n\nUse **Agent Trail** for now.\n\nGood PR link text:\n\n- View Agent Trail\n- Explore Agent Trail\n- Agent Trail for this PR\n\nAvoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\nproduct surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\nbut the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\nchange.\n\n## Product Shape\n\nA developer opens a pull request from GitButler or GitHub. GitButler adds a link\nto the pull request. A reviewer clicks that link and lands on a GitButler-owned\nweb page for the Agent Trail.\n\nThe page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\nrequest:\n\n- prompts and requests from the human\n- assistant responses and claims\n- tool calls and tool results\n- tests and validation attempts\n- decisions and tradeoffs\n- follow-up questions\n- edge cases discussed or missed\n\nThis is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. The transcript is the source of\ntruth, but the review experience should be organized around helping a reviewer\nunderstand the change.\n\n## Core Question\n\nAgent Trail should answer:\n\n> What agent context helps me review this pull request?\n\nIt should not claim:\n\n> This agent session authored this pull request.\n\nThe language should stay evidence-based. Say that a session or turn is related\nto a pull request, branch, review, or change. Do not present related agent data\nas proof of authorship.\n\n## Entry Point\n\nThe first expected entry point is a pull request link.\n\nPossible GitHub placement:\n\n- PR description link added by GitButler\n- PR comment posted by GitButler\n- check-run details link\n- GitHub app panel, if that becomes available later\n\nThe simplest first version is probably a PR description or bo\n[TRUNCATED]\nore publishing or linking:\n\n- records must be redacted\n- local filesystem paths should not be exposed\n- raw provider session ids should not be exposed\n- hidden/system/developer prompts should not be exposed\n- source records should stay bounded and redacted\n- the user should understand that the trail may contain prompts and tool output\n\nThe first product design needs an explicit publication boundary. Capturing data\ninto GitMeta does not automatically mean every pull request should expose a\npublic or team-visible Agent Trail.\n\n## Permissions\n\nOpen question: who can view an Agent Trail?\n\nPossible policy:\n\n- same users who can view the repository\n- same users who can view the pull request\n- GitButler team/workspace members\n- explicit share link recipients\n\nThe first version should pick one simple rule and make it obvious. For private\nrepositories, defaulting to repository/PR visibility is probably the least\nsurprising.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no claim that agent sessions authored the pull request\n- no full transcript dump as the main experience\n- no copying transcript records onto pull request targets\n- no product-specific review payloads inside `but-agentlog`\n- no magic generated summary as the source of truth\n- no automatic public publishing just because capture succeeded\n- no cryptographic audit or compliance story for v1\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Should the PR link be posted by GitButler Desktop, a GitButler service, or a\n  GitHub app?\n- Does Agent Trail live at a stable URL per PR, per branch, or per generated\n  snapshot?\n- Should a trail update automatically as more agent sessions are captured?\n- Should users be able to hide or exclude specific sessions before publishing?\n- What is the minimum useful privacy review before sharing a trail?\n- Should reviewers be able to ask follow-up questions against the trail?\n- Should the page include generated summaries, or only deterministic previews\n  and exact drill-down?\n\n## Implementation Boundary\n\nKeep the primitive crate boring.\n\n`but-agentlog` owns:\n\n- capture\n- redaction\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:16:18.823Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}